\pard\nowidctlpar Good question. Square root, or more generally any root  are special cases of exponential expressions. For example, sqrt(A) = A^(1/2), i.e. the square root of A is just raising A to the 1/2 power. For square root, the number inside, A, has to be positive or 0.   Hence sqrt(4) = 4^(1/2) = 2, sqrt(9) = 9^(1/2) = 3, but sqrt(-4) or (-4)^(0.5) is undefined. Similarly, the cubic root of A is equal to A^(1/3). So the priority of root operation is just as exponents. \par

