\pard\nowidctlpar Very good. As your example illustrated, when an expression or sub-expression only contains operators of the same priority level, in other words, multiplication/division or addition/subtraction, we need to evaluate it from left to right.  Please note that this rule needs to be followed during the whole evaluating process. For example, considering the following problem: 27/3^2*4=? First we take care of the highest priority operator 3^2 =9 and reduce the original expression to 27/9*4 which have only two equal-priority operators, hence we proceed from left to right: 27/9=3 ---> 27/9*4 = 3*4 =12. \par
\par
You may wonder why it has to be like this. Actually there is no particular reason. From right to left, or SADMEP all would work. These are just rules. The point is that everyone must follow the same rule otherwise we cannot communicate mathematically. But it doesn't really matter which rule is the RULE that everyone follows. It just happened that when math was in its infancy, mathematicians picked PEMDAS as the common rule. It's kind of like driving. In most US cities people drive on the right, while in US Virgin Island people drive on the left. As long as people in the same place stick to the same rule, it will be OK. \fs24\par

