\pard\nowidctlpar We need to evaluate an expression or sub-expression from left to right when it only has addition/subtraction or multiplication/division.  If it has other higher (lower) priority operators, then we need to deal with those operators first (later). The following are a few examples. (I'm going to use * and / to denote multiplication and division, respectively as is common in computer languages).\par
(1) Expr:= 2/4*6 =?  Left --> right:  Expr = 0.5*6=3 (correct); right-->left: Expr = 2/24 = 1/12 (wrong).\par
(2) Expr:=2-4+6 =? Left --> right: Expr = -2+6 =4 (correct); right -->left Expr = 2-10=-8 (wrong).\par
(3) Expr:= 2-4^2+6/2*3=?  First we evaluate sub-expression 4^2 = 16, so Expr = 2-16+3*2*2,  then evaluate sub-expression 6/2*3 (from left to right) = 3*3=9, so Expr = 2-16+9, finally we evaluate this expression (from left to right) = -14+9 = -5. \par

