Yes. You can read one of Amy Holden's post for a good graphical illustration.  But that's not the only way to multiply polynomials. As you mentioned in one of your post, the key of multiplication of two polynomials is to make sure every term in one polynomials is multipied by every term in the other one. The "box" method is just one way to make that process a bit less error-prone.  What I usually do is quite straightforward. For example, say I want to find the product of (x+1)(x^2+2x-3)=?\par
So I do (1) "1st times 1st" : x*x^2 = x^3,  (2) "1st times 2nd": x*2x = 2x^2, (3) "1st times 3rd": x*(-3) = -3x, (4) "2nd times 1st": 1*x^2 = x^2, (5) "2nd times 2nd": 1*2x = 2x ,\par
(6) "2nd times 3rd": 1*(-3) = -3.  Adding all these terms together gives x^3 + 2x^2 -3x + x^2 + 2x -3 = x^3 +3x^2 -x -3.  \par
As long as you follow the steps carefully, you should get the correct answer without much difficulty.\par

